JOHANNESBURG - Unilever South Africa and Sime Darby Hudson Knight will face prosecution for cartel activity.The reference follows an investigation by the Competition Commission which found that Unilever and Sime Darby divided markets by allocating specific types of products and customers goods in the market for the manufacturing and supply of bakery and cooking products."The Commission s investigation found that from at least 2004 to 2013 Unilever and Sime Darby entered into a Sale of Business agreement, which contained a clause in terms of which they agreed not to compete with each other in respect of certain pack sizes of margarine and edible oils," the statement from the Competition Commission explained.READ: Major banks to be prosecuted for fixing randAmong some of the arrangements between the two manufacturers, Sime Darby agreed that they would not supply industrial customers with margarine pack sizes that were less than 15kg, nor would they supply to the retail sector of the market where Unilever is active.Sime Darby had also agreed to not supply retail customers with its Crispa branded edible oils and only produce and supply 25 litre pack sizes of edible oils for industrial customers exclusively; in return Unilever would not supply industrial customers with its Flora branded edible oils."Sime Darby settled with the (Competition) Commission in 2016. The commission is seeking an order from the Competition Tribunal declaring that Unilever and Sime Darby contravened Section 4(1)(b)(ii) of the Competition Act as well as an order declaring Unilever liable for payment of an administrative penalty equal to 10% of its annual turnover," the statement went on to say.eNCA